        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Construction project management is the discipline of planning, coordinating, and controlling everything that happens between "we got the job" and "we got paid." It's not glamorous, but it's the difference between a profitable project and an expensive learning experience.</p>

        <p>This guide covers the fundamentals for contractors and new project managers who want to build systematic project management practices — not just fight fires.</p>

        <h2>The five phases of construction project management</h2>

        <h3>1. Pre-construction / Initiation</h3>
        <p>Before a shovel hits dirt, the foundation of project success is laid in pre-construction:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Scope definition:</strong> Detailed contract scope that specifies exactly what's included and explicitly calls out what isn't. Ambiguous scope creates disputes.</li>
          <li><strong>Estimating and budgeting:</strong> Building a realistic cost estimate from takeoffs, sub bids, and historical cost data. The estimate sets the baseline you'll compare actuals against.</li>
          <li><strong>Sub procurement:</strong> Soliciting, reviewing, and awarding sub bids. Written contracts with each sub, not verbal agreements.</li>
          <li><strong>Permitting and approvals:</strong> Identifying which permits are required and who's responsible for obtaining them.</li>
          <li><strong>Schedule development:</strong> Building the project schedule from scratch or from a template, with all tasks, durations, dependencies, and assigned resources.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Planning</h3>
        <p>Once the job is awarded and pre-construction complete, detailed planning defines how the work will be executed:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Production planning:</strong> Sequence of work, crew assignments, and logistics (material staging, dumpster placement, site access)</li>
          <li><strong>Risk identification:</strong> What could go wrong? Long-lead items, weather-sensitive scopes, complex inspections, challenging clients</li>
          <li><strong>Communication plan:</strong> How will you communicate with the client, subs, and your own team? What approvals are required and how will they be collected?</li>
          <li><strong>Procurement schedule:</strong> When does each material need to be ordered to arrive when needed?</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Execution</h3>
        <p>This is where the project gets built. The PM's job during execution is to keep the plan on track:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Daily coordination with subs and crew</li>
          <li>Managing the inspection process — knowing what needs to be ready before each inspection</li>
          <li>Handling changes and surprises (and there will be surprises)</li>
          <li>Documentation — daily logs, progress photos, delivery records</li>
          <li>Client communication — proactive updates so the client hears about issues from you, not because they showed up unannounced</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4. Monitoring and Control</h3>
        <p>Running parallel to execution: tracking whether the project is on schedule and on budget:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Schedule tracking:</strong> Is each phase completing on time? Where are you ahead or behind?</li>
          <li><strong>Budget tracking:</strong> Are actual costs tracking to the estimate? Which categories are running over?</li>
          <li><strong>Change order management:</strong> Identifying, pricing, and getting written approval for scope changes before doing the work</li>
          <li><strong>Risk management:</strong> Addressing identified risks as they materialize</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>5. Closeout</h3>
        <p>The phase most contractors rush through — and the one that has the most financial impact:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Punch list completion — formal inspection of all work with documented corrections</li>
          <li>Final inspections and certificate of occupancy</li>
          <li>Owner training and manual delivery (for new construction)</li>
          <li>Lien releases from all subs and suppliers</li>
          <li>Final billing and retainage collection</li>
          <li>Job cost closeout — final comparison of estimated vs. actual costs</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The project manager's daily responsibilities</h2>

        <p>On a residential construction project, a project manager's day typically includes:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Morning site walk:</strong> Check progress from prior day, confirm today's work is set up properly</li>
          <li><strong>Sub coordination:</strong> Confirm today's subs are coming, tomorrow's subs are ready, any access or delivery issues are resolved</li>
          <li><strong>Inspection scheduling:</strong> Request inspections 24–48 hours in advance, confirm predecessor work is ready</li>
          <li><strong>Client communication:</strong> Proactive update if anything has changed; answer incoming questions promptly</li>
          <li><strong>Change order documentation:</strong> Price and present any scope changes discovered that day</li>
          <li><strong>Daily log:</strong> Document what happened, who was on site, what was delivered, any issues or weather impacts</li>
          <li><strong>End-of-day schedule review:</strong> Update tomorrow's schedule based on today's actual progress</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The most important PM habits</h2>

        <h3>Document everything</h3>
        <p>The most expensive disputes in construction are the ones where someone says "that was included" and you have no written record proving otherwise. Every scope change — no matter how small — gets priced and approved in writing before the work is done. Daily logs create a timestamped record of what happened and when. Progress photos dated and organized by phase.</p>

        <h3>Communicate before problems become crises</h3>
        <p>The #1 thing that turns construction problems into relationship disasters is the client finding out about an issue by showing up at the job site unannounced, rather than hearing it from you. Get out ahead of bad news. "Here's a problem I found, here's what it means for schedule and budget, and here's how I'm solving it" is a much better conversation than "why is your dumpster in my driveway and why isn't anyone here?"</p>

        <h3>Protect your schedule like it's money</h3>
        <p>Every day a project slips costs you money — overhead allocated to that job, crew scheduled that can't work, subsequent projects pushed back. The project manager's most important job is keeping the schedule. When something threatens the schedule, escalate and solve it immediately rather than hoping it resolves itself.</p>

        <h3>Track job costs weekly</h3>
        <p>By the time a job closes, it's too late to adjust anything. The value of job cost tracking comes from seeing overruns while there's still time to recover them — or at minimum, to stop more damage. Weekly budget reviews are a fundamental PM discipline. "We're 30% over on framing labor and framing is 40% complete" is something you can respond to. "We went over on framing" discovered at closeout is just a loss.</p>

        <h2>Project management tools for contractors</h2>

        <h3>The minimum viable PM system</h3>
        <p>For a solo contractor or small team just getting started with systematic PM:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Estimating template (spreadsheet or software)</li>
          <li>Written contracts for every job (standard form plus scope-specific riders)</li>
          <li>Daily log (can be simple notes, but must be done daily)</li>
          <li>Change order form (written and signed before work starts)</li>
          <li>Budget vs. actual spreadsheet updated weekly</li>
        </ul>

        <p>This system costs nothing but time and discipline. It's better than what most small contractors do.</p>

