        <h2>Common construction PM mistakes (and how to avoid them)</h2>

        <h3>Verbal scope changes</h3>
        <p><strong>The mistake:</strong> Client asks for a change on-site, you say yes and do the work, then bill for it — and the client says "I never asked for that."</p>
        <p><strong>The fix:</strong> Every scope change, no matter how small, gets a written change order signed before work starts. This protects both parties. Most clients appreciate the clarity; the ones who resist written change orders are the ones you'll have disputes with later.</p>

        <h3>Scheduling subs without commitment</h3>
        <p><strong>The mistake:</strong> You "tentatively" schedule your electrician for Week 4. Week 4 arrives, the electrician has another job. Your project sits idle.</p>
        <p><strong>The fix:</strong> Confirm all sub schedules in writing (text or email is sufficient) with specific dates, not ranges. Follow up 3–5 days before their scheduled start. Have backup subs identified for critical path trades.</p>

        <h3>Not collecting retainage until too late</h3>
        <p><strong>The mistake:</strong> Final payment invoice sent at closeout. Client finds multiple punchlist items. Uses payment leverage to extract additional scope.</p>
        <p><strong>The fix:</strong> Structured payment schedule tied to milestones. Final payment requires only the agreed-upon punchlist, not any additional scope the client thinks of after seeing the completed work. Document the punchlist, complete it, confirm with the client, collect payment.</p>

        <h3>Not using a schedule template</h3>
        <p><strong>The mistake:</strong> Building a schedule from scratch for every project. Takes 2–3 hours and you still forget something.</p>
        <p><strong>The fix:</strong> Create a master schedule template for each project type you do regularly. Apply it to new projects, adjust for project-specific conditions, done in 30 minutes. Construction PM software like Buildertrend and JobTread support schedule templates.</p>

